## Slide 13 — Storage Architecture

### Three backends, one abstraction

```mermaid
flowchart TB
    API["API"] --> SA["Storage Abstraction\nBaseStorage"]
    SA --> Local["LocalStorage\n~/.memdog"]
    SA --> GCS2["GCSStorage\nGoogle Cloud Storage"]
    SA --> Supa["SupabaseStorage\nPostgres + GCS hybrid"]

    Supa --> BlobT["mem_dog_blobs\nstructured data"]
    Supa --> EmbT["mem_dog_embeddings\npgvector"]
    Supa --> EntT["mem_dog_entities\nknowledge graph"]
    Supa --> RelT["mem_dog_relationships\nentity links"]
    Supa --> GCS3["GCS\nraw binary blobs"]
```

**Supabase (production):**
- All metadata, memories, tags, versions in `mem_dog_blobs`
- Vector embeddings in `mem_dog_embeddings` (pgvector with cosine similarity)
- Knowledge graph in `mem_dog_entities` + `mem_dog_relationships`
- Raw binary files in GCS (images, PDFs, audio, video)
- Per-user scoping on every table and query

---

## Slide 14 — Security & Observability

### Security

| Layer | Implementation |
|-------|---------------|
| **Authentication** | Supabase Auth (email + Google OAuth) + per-user API keys |
| **Authorization** | Per-item ACLs, per-user scoping on every query |
| **Encryption** | Fernet AES-256 for all stored credentials |
| **API Auth** | Dual-path: global API key or per-user `md_<token>` |
| **Channel Security** | Per-channel signature verification (Slack, Telegram, etc.) |
| **Data Isolation** | user_id scoping on storage, embeddings, graph, memories |

### Observability

| Feature | Implementation |
|---------|---------------|
| **Distributed Tracing** | OpenTelemetry across all components |
| **Span Viewer** | Waterfall UI in the Insights tab |
| **Token Tracking** | Per-user, per-model, per-agent token usage |
| **Stats Dashboard** | Data counts, embedding counts, memory usage |

---

## Slide 15 — Sustainable AI Design

### Efficiency at every layer

| Strategy | Implementation | Saving |
|----------|---------------|--------|
| **Model routing** | 6-layer deterministic classifier + tiered agents | 50-95% cost |
| **Small models** | gemma3:4b default, 12b/27b only when needed | ~90% energy vs frontier |
| **Async pipeline** | NATS queue, non-realtime enrichment | 30-50% energy |
| **Context optimization** | Content truncation, typed prompts, max_tokens limits | 20-60% cost |
| **Caching** | Routing config, model catalog, stats | 30-80% cost |
| **Self-hosting** | In-cluster Ollama, Ollama Cloud, Gemini fallback only | 70-90% cost |

No frontier model in the default pipeline. Gemini serves only as fallback.

---

## Slide 16 — How memdog Compares

### vs. mem0 and other memory platforms

| Feature | memdog | mem0 |
|---------|---------|------|
| Multi-channel ingest | 25+ channels + DigiMe agent | API only |
| AI enrichment pipeline | 40 typed agents, auto on ingest | Basic extraction |
| Data type coverage | 60+ types (media, spatial, IoT, medical) | Text-focused |
| Knowledge graph | Postgres (auto-extracted entities) | Neo4j (separate infra) |
| Simple SDK | `MemDog` with 8 methods | `Memory` with add/search/get |
| Agent adapters | LangChain, CrewAI, OpenAI | LangChain, CrewAI, others |
| Memory compression | LLM summarization + archive | Not available |
| Storage backends | Local, GCS, Supabase | Cloud-only |
| Self-hosting | Docker Compose or GKE, Mac Mini | Cloud service |
| Model flexibility | 5 tiers, Model Garden, BYO provider | Single model |
| Web UI | Full management + RAG chat | Dashboard |
| Versioning | Every mutation tracked | Not available |
| Integration platform | 300+ providers, OAuth2, encrypted creds | Limited |

